===Glyph origin===
{{Han etyl}}
{{Han compound|иҮӘ|t1=nose|з•Җ|ls=psc|c1=s|c2=p|no_och1=y}}.

{{och-l|*иҮӘ}} originally referred to this word, but came to be used to refer to {{och-l|иҮӘ|self}} instead, so the sense of вҖңnoseвҖқ has been replaced by this character. Some scholars interpret {{och-l|йј»*}} as a combination of a nose ({{och-l|*иҮӘ}}) and two lungs ({{och-l|*з•Җ}}), however {{lang|zh|sc=Hani|з•Җ}} on oracle bones represents an arrow.

===Etymology===
From {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*bi||nose}}; compare {{cog|ii|к…ікҒ–|к…і'''кҒ–'''|nose; snot}}.

Alternatively, it may be from {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*s-brit||sneeze; nose; swallow}}, whence {{cog|bo|аҪҰаҫҰаҫІаҪІаҪ‘||sneeze}}, but there is no trace of ''r'' in Chinese ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).

In some modern lects, including Mandarin, Gan, Jin, Wu, and Xiang, and even in the literary layer of some Min dialects, the word reflects a form with final ''*-t''. For example, in standard Mandarin, the word is pronounced ''bГӯ'' (implying an old entering tone) instead of ''bГ¬'' (the expected reflex from the departing tone in Middle Chinese). This is due to a phonological phenomenon in the northwest, either an early loss of ''*-s'' in the ''*-ts'' cluster before regular final cluster simplification occurred ({{zh-ref|Baxter, 1992}}), or a dialectal change from ''*-s'' to ''*-t'' ({{zh-ref|Pulleybank, 1998}}).

